Mean imputation

We will address missing data:

  • By subscale (based on theory that maltreatment is multidimensional, we will only use information from within the same subscale, rather than across all subscales, to infer missing responses)
  • All subscales have 5 questions; we will calculate a score if <2 items are missing (subscale is at least 80% complete)
  • This calculation will be a mean imputation (missing response = average of answered items on subscale x 5 questions per subscale)

Define variable subsets for each subscale

# emotional abuse (ea)
ctq_ea_vars <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(q3...6, q8...11, q14...17, q18...21, q25...28) %>%
    names()

# physical abuse (pa)
ctq_pa_vars <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(q9...12, q11...14, q12...15, q15...18, q17...20) %>%
    names()

# sexual abuse (sa)
ctq_sa_vars <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(q20...23, q21...24, q23...26, q24...27, q27...30) %>%
    names()

# emotional neglect (en)
ctq_en_vars <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(q5_r, q7_r, q13_r, q19_r, q28_r) %>%
    names()

# physical neglect (pn)
ctq_pn_vars <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(q1...4, q2_r, q4...7, q6...9, q26_r) %>%
    names()

Calculate row means for each subscale

# grab question variables
ctq_question_vars <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(contains("q")) %>%
    names()

# convert questions to numeric type
ctq_data_clean <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    mutate_at(vars(ctq_question_vars), list(~as.double(.)))

# calculate row means
ctq_data_clean$ea_row_means <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(., ctq_ea_vars) %>%
    rowMeans(na.rm = T)

ctq_data_clean$sa_row_means <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(., ctq_sa_vars) %>%
    rowMeans(na.rm = T)

ctq_data_clean$pa_row_means <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(., ctq_pa_vars) %>%
    rowMeans(na.rm = T)

ctq_data_clean$en_row_means <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(., ctq_en_vars) %>%
    rowMeans(na.rm = T)

ctq_data_clean$pn_row_means <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(., ctq_pn_vars) %>%
    rowMeans(na.rm = T)

Mean imputation for non-complete rows by subscale

# determine which rows are more than 70% complete (at least
# 4/5 questions answered per subscale - 3/5 would be 60%
# complete, 4/5 is >70% complete or 80% complete)
ea_complete = more_than_c_percent_complete(ctq_data_clean, ctq_ea_vars,
    0.7)
## Note: Using an external vector in selections is ambiguous.
##  Use `all_of(y)` instead of `y` to silence this message.
##  See <https://tidyselect.r-lib.org/reference/faq-external-vector.html>.
## This message is displayed once per session.
# If the ea subset is more than 70% complete for each row,
# replace the NAs with the row's ea mean
replace_na_with_mean(ctq_data_clean, ctq_ea_vars, ea_complete,
    ea_row_means)

# Same steps as above, for sa variables
sa_complete = more_than_c_percent_complete(ctq_data_clean, ctq_sa_vars,
    0.7)

replace_na_with_mean(ctq_data_clean, ctq_sa_vars, sa_complete,
    sa_row_means)

# Same steps as above, for pa variables
pa_complete = more_than_c_percent_complete(ctq_data_clean, ctq_pa_vars,
    0.7)

replace_na_with_mean(ctq_data_clean, ctq_pa_vars, pa_complete,
    pa_row_means)

# Same steps as above, for en variables
en_complete = more_than_c_percent_complete(ctq_data_clean, ctq_en_vars,
    0.7)

replace_na_with_mean(ctq_data_clean, ctq_en_vars, en_complete,
    en_row_means)

# Same steps as above, for pn variables
pn_complete = more_than_c_percent_complete(ctq_data_clean, ctq_pn_vars,
    0.7)

replace_na_with_mean(ctq_data_clean, ctq_pn_vars, pn_complete,
    pn_row_means)

Calculate subscale scores

each scales range = 5-25

# calculate subscale scores
ctq_data_clean <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    mutate(ctq_ea_score = q3...6 + q8...11 + q14...17 + q18...21 +
        q25...28, ctq_pa_score = q9...12 + q11...14 + q12...15 +
        q15...18 + q17...20, ctq_sa_score = q20...23 + q21...24 +
        q23...26 + q24...27 + q27...30, ctq_en_score = q5_r +
        q7_r + q13_r + q19_r + q28_r, ctq_pn_score = q1...4 +
        q2_r + q4...7 + q6...9 + q26_r)

Calculate CTQ total score (range = 25-100)

ctq_data_clean <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    mutate(ctq_total_score = ctq_ea_score + ctq_en_score + ctq_pa_score +
        ctq_pn_score + ctq_sa_score)

Calculate binary maltreated category (yes=1, no=0)

Individual is categorized as maltreated if they score above cutoff for slight/moderate or moderate/severe maltreatment on at least 1 subscale. This was the strategy used in Church et al., 2017

Cutoffs are:

Type Slight/Mod Mod/Severe
EA: 9 13
PA: 8 10
SA: 6 8
EN: 10 15
PN: 8 10 
ctq_data_clean <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    mutate(maltreated = ifelse(ctq_ea_score > 8 | ctq_pa_score >
        7 | ctq_sa_score > 5 | ctq_en_score > 9 | ctq_pn_score >
        7, 1, 0), maltreated_mod = ifelse(ctq_ea_score > 12 |
        ctq_pa_score > 9 | ctq_sa_score > 7 | ctq_en_score >
        14 | ctq_pn_score > 9, 1, 0))

Select score variables to save in scores dataset

ctq_data_tosave <- ctq_data_clean %>%
    dplyr::select(subjid, c(ctq_ea_score:maltreated_mod), person_filling)

# determine which year/month of child's life the data is
# from, extract that part of the file name
year <- substr(substring(ctq_file, regexpr("(_[M|Y][0-9]?[1-9]_)",
    ctq_file)), 1, 4)

# change column names to include child age at collection
colnames(ctq_data_tosave) <- paste0(colnames(ctq_data_tosave),
    year)
# change first column name back (because ID is constant
# across age and needs to be the same so we can merge
# files)
colnames(ctq_data_tosave)[1] <- str_replace(colnames(ctq_data_tosave)[1],
    year, "")

Select variables to save in item-level dataset

#rename variables and get rid of unneeded ones
ctq_data_items <-
  ctq_data_clean %>% 
  rename_with(., ~str_replace_all(.x, "([.][.][.][1-9][0-9]?)", ""), contains("...")) %>% # rename vars to get rid of ...
  dplyr::select(
    -q2,
    -q5,
    -q7,
    -q13,
    -q19,
    -q26,
    -q28,
    -comments_box,
    -ea_row_means,
    -sa_row_means,
    -pa_row_means,
    -en_row_means,
    -pn_row_means,
    -maltreated,
    -maltreated_mod
    ) #get rid of variables that were reverse-coded, extraneous variables, and scores

#rename all variables that do not already have "ctq_" at the beginning to contain that for merging
ctq_data_items <-
  ctq_data_items %>% 
  rename_with(., ~str_c("ctq_", .x), !contains("ctq_"))

#filter out cases that were not completed by mothers, then remove person_filling variables and score variables 
ctq_data_items <-
  ctq_data_items %>% 
  filter(ctq_person_filling == "Mother") %>% 
  dplyr::select(
    -ctq_person_filling,
    -ctq_others_specify_text,
    -contains("score")
  )

Save output files

# create file names which contains today's date and child
# age data were collected in years
scores_file_name <- str_c("../../data/mother_childhood/GUSTO",
    year, "_CTQ_scores_", str_replace_all(Sys.Date(), "-", ""),
    ".csv")

items_file_name <- str_c("../../data/mother_childhood/GUSTO",
    year, "_CTQ_items_", str_replace_all(Sys.Date(), "-", ""),
    ".csv")

# write output - scores
write_csv(ctq_data_tosave, scores_file_name)

# write output - item-level
write_csv(ctq_data_items, items_file_name)
